{"title_page": "Peter FitzSimons", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name = Peter FitzSimons\n|image = Pete FitzSimons (cropped).jpg\n|caption =\n|birth_name = Peter John FitzSimons\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|6|29|df=y}}\n|birth_place = Sydney, Australia\n|occupation = {{hlist|Journalist|writer|radio and television personality|former rugby union football player}}\n|years active = 1987\u2212present\n|genre = Non-fiction\n|spouse = {{marriage|[[Lisa Wilkinson]]|1992}}\n|children = 3\n|alma_mater = [[University of Sydney]]\n}}\n\n'''Peter John FitzSimons'''<ref name=scrum/> {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM}} (born 29 June 1961) is an Australian author, journalist, radio and television presenter. He is a former [[Australia national rugby union team|national representative]] rugby union player and has been the chair of the [[Australian Republic Movement]] since 2015.\n\n==Early life==\nFitzSimons grew up in [[Peats Ridge, New South Wales|Peats Ridge]],<ref>[http://mosmanis.info/walloffame/web/sportsperson.php?id=44 Mosman Sporting Wall of Fame: Peter FitzSimons' profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903045753/http://mosmanis.info/walloffame/web/sportsperson.php?id=44 |date=3 September 2009 }}</ref> in the [[Central Coast (New South Wales)|Central Coast]] of New South Wales. He was one of seven children. He attended Peats Ridge Primary School, and [[Knox Grammar School]] before going in 1978 to [[Findlay High School]], Ohio,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/the-fitz-files/sorry-if-i-offended-anyone-but-were-all-a-mob-of-bastards-20160520-goznz9.html|title=Sorry if I offended anyone, but we're all a mob of bastards|first=Peter |last=FitzSimons|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=21 May 2016|access-date=}}</ref> for a year as an [[exchange student]] on an [[AFS Intercultural Programs|American Field Service Scholarship]]. He then completed an arts degree at the [[University of Sydney]],<ref>[http://www.celebrityspeakers.com.au/after-dinner-speakers/peter-fitzsimons Speaker Profile of Peter FitzSimons at The Celebrity Speakers Bureau]</ref> residing at [[Wesley College, University of Sydney|Wesley College]] from 1980 to 1982.<ref>{{cite news|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|title=Given time, great colleges learn to fix their problems|url=http://www.smh.com.au/it-pro/given-time-great-colleges-learn-to-fix-their-problems-20121108-290tj.html|accessdate=4 December 2014|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=9 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Rugby===\nFitzSimons first played club rugby with the [[Sydney University Football Club]] and then with the [[Manly RUFC]] in Sydney in the 1980s under the coaching of [[Alan Jones (radio broadcaster)|Alan Jones]].<ref name=scrum>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/australia/rugby/player/10666.html|title=Player profile of Peter FitzSimons|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=3 October 2010}}</ref> Between 1985 and 1989 he played with [[CA Brive]] in France for four seasons as the club's first foreign player. He played seven [[Test match (rugby union)|test matches]] at [[Lock (rugby union)|lock]] for the [[Australia national rugby union team|Australian national rugby union team]] between 1989 and 1990, debuting against [[France national rugby union team|France]] in Strasbourg in November 1989, on the Wallabies 1989 tour of Europe. His final Test match was against the [[All Blacks]] in Christchurch.<ref name=scrum-22297>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnscrum.com/australia/rugby/match/22297.html|title=Match report: New Zealand Australia, 21 July 1990|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nFormer Wallabies winger [[David Campese]] has criticised FitzSimons for starting a brawl in Australia's first Test against France in 1990.<ref name=campese/>{{rp|117, 166}} Campese labelled FitzSimons' actions \"a disgrace to the good name of rugby\"<ref name=campese>{{cite book|author1=Campese, David|author-link1=David Campese|last2=Bills|first2=Peter|title=On a Wing and a Prayer|publisher=Queen Anne Press|year=1991|isbn=0-356-17958-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/onwingprayerauto00camp}}</ref>{{rp|117}} and asserted that \"he was doing the game and its reputation enormous damage.\"<ref name=campese/>{{rp|166}} Campese cautioned that if such fights \"turn even one family away from the game, then they have been too costly\".<ref name=campese/>{{rp|166}}\n\nFormer [[Australia national rugby union team|Wallabies]] [[Rugby_union_positions#Back_row_(Loose_forwards)|backrower]] [[Viliami Ofahengaue|Willie Ofahengaue]] said of FitzSimons: \"He's a big character. Funny guy. Talkative. One thing I remember about rooming with him was he used to get his suitcase, tip it up and pour everything out on to the floor. When it was time to go home he would chuck everything back in any old way. Fitzy was a real roughie, but he is married now so he must have changed.\"<ref>[https://www.couriermail.com.au/ipad/big-o-far-from-the-end-of-the-line/news-story/ae9d9eaba0892d70eade3dc0aacdd189 Courier Mail]</ref>\n\n===Journalist===\nFitzSimons has written for ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' since 1988,<ref>His first article as a ''Herald'' correspondent was \"From the Wilds of France\": [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qXVWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zeQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2616%2C940763 FitzSimons, P., \"The survivors of la Besse still remember\", ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', (Tuesday, 22 November 1988), p. 23.]</ref> and has been a sports [[columnist]] for that publication since 1987.<ref>His first article as a ''Herald'' sports journalist was: [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uCtWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w-QDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2310%2C6147021 FitzSimons, P., \"French give Scots some pointers\", ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 9 March 1987, p. 53.]</ref> He regularly appears on the Australian [[Foxtel]] programme, ''[[The Back Page]]'', formerly hosted by rugby league journalist [[Mike Gibson (sports journalist)|Mike Gibson]] and now [[Tony Squires]]. For the Saturday edition of ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', FitzSimons writes a column titled \"The Fitz Files\" which looks at all the happenings over the past seven days in sport. He writes a more general version of \"The Fitz Files\" in ''[[The Sun-Herald]]'' on Sundays, focusing on community activities and events in Sydney. [[Andrew Denton]] has called him \"Australia's finest sports journalist\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/qanda/txt/s2876991.htm|title=Panelist: Peter FitzSimons|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|work=Q&A|accessdate=26 February 2012}}</ref> On the 25 September 2001 he wrote a thought provoking opinion editorial piece titled Memo world: try saying sorry to avoid a sorry end.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peter FitzSimons |title=Memo world: try saying sorry to avoid a sorry end |url=http://old.smh.com.au/news/0109/25/opinion/opinion3.html |accessdate=20 May 2019 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=25 September 2001 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030205060337/http://old.smh.com.au/news/0109/25/opinion/opinion3.html |archivedate=5 February 2003 |language=en |quote=We accept that such hate as drove the planes into the World Trade Centre towers can only have come from incredible suffering, and we are desperately sorry for that suffering}}</ref>\n\n===Radio===\nIn January 2006 FitzSimons began co-hosting a breakfast radio program with [[Mike Carlton]] on Sydney radio station [[2UE]]. He was brought onto the 2UE breakfast show in an attempt to boost the program's dwindling ratings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/tv--radio/the-odd-couple/2006/01/21/1137734186701.html|title=The odd couple|first=Sue|last=Javes|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=23 January 2006}}</ref> However, the ''Mike and Fitz Breakfast Show'' still trailed a long way behind the number one program on [[2GB]], hosted by FitzSimons' former coach Alan Jones.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/mike-carlton-quits-radio-returns-to-smh/news-story/ec26b075894a690dcbf9d2828de42197|title=Mike Carlton quits 2UE radio breakfast slot|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=7 September 2009}}</ref> After two years, FitzSimons quit to become a [[stay-at-home dad]] and focus on his writing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/radio-battle-for-fitz-vacancy/news-story/3adcb06b27ac54f3ed693620b338cf8f|title=Radio battle for Fitz vacancy|first=Fiona|last=Connolly|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=7 November 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n[[File:Peter FitzSimons (8446505665).jpg|thumb|FitzSimons with his trademark red [[bandana]]<ref>[https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/republic-no-sure-thing-says-peter-fitzsimons/news-story/c28fc89fb3e0ade25fa344b9f75bf3e3 \"Republic no sure thing, says Peter FitzSimons\"] by Ben Packham, ''[[The Australian]]'', 12 November 2018 {{subscription}}</ref>]]\nFitzSimons' published works include:\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Basking in Beirut and other adventures with Peter FitzSimons|publication-date=1991|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-86373-052-5 }}\n* with{{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|author2=Kogler, Brian|title=Little theories of life|publication-date=1991|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-86373-109-6 }}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Rugby stories: some rucking good yarns|publication-date=1993|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-86373-440-0}}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Nick Farr-Jones: the authorised biography|publication-date=1993|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=978-0-09-182758-8}}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Hitchhiking for ugly people: and other life experiences|publication-date=1994|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=978-0-09-182967-4}}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=The rugby war|publication-date=1996|publisher=HarperSports|isbn=978-0-7322-5687-6}}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Everyone but Phar Lap: face to face with the best of Australian sport|publication-date=1997|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-7322-6409-3}}\n* with{{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|author2=Blair, Tony|title=Beazley: a biography|publication-date=1998|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-7322-6521-2}}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=FitzSimons on rugby: loose in the tight five|publication-date=1999|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-86508-132-8}}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Nancy Wake: a biography of our greatest war heroine|publication-date=2001|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-7322-6919-7}}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=John Eales: the biography|publication-date=2001|publisher=ABC Books for the Australian Broadcasting Corporation|isbn=978-1-85291-644-2}}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Nene|publication-date=2002|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-7322-7565-5}}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Steve Waugh|publication-date=2004|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-7322-7647-8}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Tobruk|date=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|location=Pymble|isbn=9780732291563}}\n* {{cite book|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Great Australian sports champions|publication-date=2006|publisher=HarperSports|isbn=978-0-7322-8517-3}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=The ballad of Les Darcy|publication-date=2007|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|isbn=978-0-7322-8636-1}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=And now for some light relief: the genuinely funny joke book|publication-date=2009|publisher=Ebury |isbn=978-1-74166-901-5}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Kokoda|date=2010|publisher=Hachette UK|isbn=9780733626067}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Charles Kingsford Smith and those magnificent men|date=2010|publisher=HarperCollins|location=Pymble|isbn=9780732288198}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=A Simpler Time|date=2010|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|location=Pymble|isbn=9780730492511}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Mawson|date=2011|publisher=William Heinemann|location=North Sydney|isbn=9781742754581}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Batavia|date=2012|publisher=Random House Australia|location=North Sydney|isbn=9781864711349}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Eureka: the unfinished revolution|date=2013|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=9780857981271}}\n* {{cite book|editor1=Growden, Greg|editor2=FitzSimons, Peter|title=More important than life or death: inside the best of Australian sport|publication-date=2013|location=Crows Nest|publisher=Fairfax Books|isbn=978-1-74331-319-0}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Ned Kelly|date=2013|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=9781742758916}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Gallipoli|date=2014|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=9780857984562}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Fromelles and Pozi\u00e8res: In the trenches of Hell|date=2015|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=9781742759517}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Gotta love this country!|publication-date=2015|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-76029-048-1}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=The Great Aussie Bloke Slim-Down: How an Over-50 Former Footballer Went From Fat to Fit... and Lost 45 Kilos|publisher=Penguin Books Australia|publication-date=2016|isbn=9780143781868}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Victory at Villers-Bretonneux: Why a French town will never forget the Anzacs|date=2016|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=9781742759531}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|others=illustrated by Reg Lynch|title=Seriously ... you have to laugh: great yarns and tall tales from the sporting fields, dressing rooms and commentary boxes of Australia|publication-date=2016|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-76029-399-4}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Burke and Wills: The Triumph and Tragedy of Australia's Most Famous Explorers|date=2017|publisher=Hachette Australia|isbn=9780733634109}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Monash's masterpiece: the battle of Le Hamel and the 93 minutes that changed the world|publication-date=2018|publisher=Hachette Australia|isbn=978-0-7336-4008-7}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Mutiny on the Bounty: A saga of sex, sedition, mayhem and mutiny|publication-date=2018|publisher=Hachette Australia|isbn=978-0-7336-3411-6}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=The Catalpa Rescue: The gripping story of the most dramatic and successful prison break in Australian history|publication-date=2019|publisher=Hachette Australia|isbn=978-0-7336-4124-4}}\n* {{cite book|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=James Cook: The Story Behind the Man who Mapped the World|publication-date=2019|publisher=Hachette Australia|isbn=978-0-7336-4127-5}}\n\n===Community activity===\nFitzSimons is or was involved with a range of community organisations. He was a fellow of the Senate of [[University of Sydney]] from 2009 to 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sydney.edu.au/senate/FitzSimons.shtml|title=Fellows of the Senate: Peter John FitzSimons|date=|access-date=|publisher=[[University of Sydney]]}}</ref> a [[patronage|patron]] of The [[Russell Prize]] for Humour Writing, [[State Library of New South Wales]], since 2015<ref>[https://www.booksandpublishing.com.au/articles/2014/12/17/32004/nsw-state-library-launches-humour-writing-prize/ \"NSW State Library launches humour-writing prize\"], Books + Publishing, 17 December 2014</ref> and chairman of the [[Australian Republic Movement]] since 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/jul/20/peter-fitzsimons-appointed-head-of-australian-republican-movement|title=Peter FitzSimons appointed head of Australian Republican Movement|date=20 July 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the lead up to [[2019 New South Wales state election]], FitzSimons began a campaign to prevent the demolition of the [[Sydney Football Stadium]] and [[Stadium Australia]]. He began by launching a petition in late 2017 on [[Change.org]] that reached approximately 220,000 signatures prior to the election as well as numerous editorial articles decrying the demolitions. The stadium issue became a major element of the campaign with Labor leader [[Michael Daley]] calling the election a \"referendum on stadiums\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/nsw/i-will-not-be-bullied-daley-holds-firm-on-stadiums-policy-20181202-p50jpa.html |title='I will not be bullied': Daley holds firm on stadiums policy |last=Smith |first=Alexandra |date=3 December 2018|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=4 April 2019 |quote=The new Labor leader says the state election would be a referendum on stadiums}}</ref> On 5 December 2017, FitzSimons remarked on [[Twitter]] that the incumbent [[Gladys Berejiklian]] government could \"bulldoze and rebuild three new stadiums, including Parra, for $3Billion \u2013 on no demand \u2013 or they can win the next election, but they can't do both.\"<ref>{{Cite tweet|author=Peter FitzSimons|user=Peter_Fitz|title=(untitled)|date=5 December 2017|number=937843739736674304}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Berejiklian and her coalition were easily returned to government, with political commentators suggesting that the issue did not resonate with the wider community of the state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-25/the-sydney-stadium-wars-are-over,-and-the-people-have-spoken/10934488 |title=Sydney stadium wars ended by Coalition's NSW election victory as people vote for an upgrade |last=Hinds |first=Richards |date=25 March 2019 |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|access-date=4 April 2019 |quote=it is possible to say with confidence there was one thing Sydneysiders did not vote against \u2014 new or refurbished stadiums.}}</ref> The campaign had a minor success however, as the Government changed the original plan for a complete knock down rebuild of Stadium Australia, and instead would go ahead with a billion dollar refurbishment.\n\n==Personal life==\nFitzSimons is married to Australian journalist and TV presenter [[Lisa Wilkinson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/entertainment/photos-e6frg30l-1226487265216?page=4|title=Galleries: 1992 Weddings|work=[[Perth Now]]|page=4|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> They have three children and live in Sydney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/lifestyle/today-show-hosts-a-perfect-match/story-e6frf039-1225896224840|title=Today show hosts a perfect match|first=Richard|last=Clune|work=[[The Sunday Telegraph (Sydney)|The Sunday Telegraph]]|location=Sydney|date=25 July 2010|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nFitzSimons has identified himself as a communist .<ref>[http://www.meetup.com/sydneyatheists/events/68134322/ \"Is Religion a Con? A special evening with Peter FitzSimons\"], 12 June 2012, The Independent Theatre</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nOn 13 June 2011 FitzSimons was named a [[Order of Australia|Member of the Order of Australia]] for service to literature as a biographer, sports journalist and commentator, and to the community through contributions to conservation, disability care, social welfare and sporting organisations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peter FitzSimons AM|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1144271&search_type=quick&showInd=true|publisher=Australian Honours Database|accessdate=13 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=[[Australian Associated Press]]|title=Former Wallaby FitzSimons honoured|url=http://my.rugby.com.au/news/aap/s-786352_former_wallaby_fitzsimons_honoured,147625.html/news/archive/section/21893|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120719040442/http://my.rugby.com.au/news/aap/s-786352_former_wallaby_fitzsimons_honoured,147625.html/news/archive/section/21893|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 July 2012|publisher=[[Australian Rugby Union]]|date=13 June 2011|accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{Commons category|Peter FitzSimons}}\n* [http://www.smh.com.au/sport/by/Peter-FitzSimons-hvemu Homepage for FitzSimons' columns] in ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''\n* {{official|http://peterfitzsimons.com.au/}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:FitzSimons, Peter}}\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian biographers]]\n[[Category:Male biographers]]\n[[Category:Australian columnists]]\n[[Category:Australian radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Australian sportswriters]]\n[[Category:Australian television personalities]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian republicans]]\n[[Category:People educated at Knox Grammar School]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Sydney]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Expatriate rugby union players in France]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Australia international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Australian atheists]]\n[[Category:Australian conservationists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Australian memoirists]]\n[[Category:Australian non-fiction crime writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name = Peter FitzSimons\n|image = Pete FitzSimons (cropped).jpg\n|caption =\n|birth_name = Peter John FitzSimons\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|6|29|df=y}}\n|birth_place = Sydney, Australia\n|occupation = {{hlist|Journalist|writer|radio and television personality|former rugby union football player}}\n|years active = 1987\u2212present\n|genre = Non-fiction\n|spouse = {{marriage|[[Lisa Wilkinson]]|1992}}\n|children = 3\n|alma_mater = [[University of Sydney]]\n}}\n\n'''Peter John FitzSimons'''<ref name=scrum/> {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM}} (born 29 June 1961) is an Australian author, journalist, radio and television presenter. He is a former [[Australia national rugby union team|national representative]] rugby union player and has been the chair of the [[Australian Republic Movement]] since 2015.\n\n==Early life==\nFitzSimons grew up in [[Peats Ridge, New South Wales|Peats Ridge]],<ref>[http://mosmanis.info/walloffame/web/sportsperson.php?id=44 Mosman Sporting Wall of Fame: Peter FitzSimons' profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903045753/http://mosmanis.info/walloffame/web/sportsperson.php?id=44 |date=3 September 2009 }}</ref> in the [[Central Coast (New South Wales)|Central Coast]] of New South Wales. He was one of seven children. He attended Peats Ridge Primary School, and [[Knox Grammar School]] before going in 1978 to [[Findlay High School]], Ohio,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/the-fitz-files/sorry-if-i-offended-anyone-but-were-all-a-mob-of-bastards-20160520-goznz9.html|title=Sorry if I offended anyone, but we're all a mob of bastards|first=Peter |last=FitzSimons|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=21 May 2016|access-date=}}</ref> for a year as an [[exchange student]] on an [[AFS Intercultural Programs|American Field Service Scholarship]]. He then completed an arts degree at the [[University of Sydney]],<ref>[http://www.celebrityspeakers.com.au/after-dinner-speakers/peter-fitzsimons Speaker Profile of Peter FitzSimons at The Celebrity Speakers Bureau]</ref> residing at [[Wesley College, University of Sydney|Wesley College]] from 1980 to 1982.<ref>{{cite news|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|title=Given time, great colleges learn to fix their problems|url=http://www.smh.com.au/it-pro/given-time-great-colleges-learn-to-fix-their-problems-20121108-290tj.html|accessdate=4 December 2014|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=9 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Rugby===\nFitzSimons first played club rugby with the [[Sydney University Football Club]] and then with the [[Manly RUFC]] in Sydney in the 1980s under the coaching of [[Alan Jones (radio broadcaster)|Alan Jones]].<ref name=scrum>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/australia/rugby/player/10666.html|title=Player profile of Peter FitzSimons|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=3 October 2010}}</ref> Between 1985 and 1989 he played with [[CA Brive]] in France for four seasons as the club's first foreign player. He played seven [[Test match (rugby union)|test matches]] at [[Lock (rugby union)|lock]] for the [[Australia national rugby union team|Australian national rugby union team]] between 1989 and 1990, debuting against [[France national rugby union team|France]] in Strasbourg in November 1989, on the Wallabies 1989 tour of Europe. His final Test match was against the [[All Blacks]] in Christchurch.<ref name=scrum-22297>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnscrum.com/australia/rugby/match/22297.html|title=Match report: New Zealand Australia, 21 July 1990|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nFormer Wallabies winger [[David Campese]] has criticised FitzSimons for starting a brawl in Australia's first Test against France in 1990.<ref name=campese/>{{rp|117, 166}} Campese labelled FitzSimons' actions \"a disgrace to the good name of rugby\"<ref name=campese>{{cite book|author1=Campese, David|author-link1=David Campese|last2=Bills|first2=Peter|title=On a Wing and a Prayer|publisher=Queen Anne Press|year=1991|isbn=0-356-17958-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/onwingprayerauto00camp}}</ref>{{rp|117}} and asserted that \"he was doing the game and its reputation enormous damage.\"<ref name=campese/>{{rp|166}} Campese cautioned that if such fights \"turn even one family away from the game, then they have been too costly\".<ref name=campese/>{{rp|166}}\n\nFormer [[Australia national rugby union team|Wallabies]] [[Rugby_union_positions#Back_row_(Loose_forwards)|backrower]] [[Viliami Ofahengaue|Willie Ofahengaue]] said of FitzSimons: \"He's a big character. Funny guy. Talkative. One thing I remember about rooming with him was he used to get his suitcase, tip it up and pour everything out on to the floor. When it was time to go home he would chuck everything back in any old way. Fitzy was a real roughie, but he is married now so he must have changed.\"<ref>[https://www.couriermail.com.au/ipad/big-o-far-from-the-end-of-the-line/news-story/ae9d9eaba0892d70eade3dc0aacdd189 Courier Mail]</ref>\n\n===Journalist===\nFitzSimons has written for ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' since 1988,<ref>His first article as a ''Herald'' correspondent was \"From the Wilds of France\": [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qXVWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zeQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2616%2C940763 FitzSimons, P., \"The survivors of la Besse still remember\", ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', (Tuesday, 22 November 1988), p. 23.]</ref> and has been a sports [[columnist]] for that publication since 1987.<ref>His first article as a ''Herald'' sports journalist was: [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uCtWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w-QDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2310%2C6147021 FitzSimons, P., \"French give Scots some pointers\", ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 9 March 1987, p. 53.]</ref> He regularly appears on the Australian [[Foxtel]] programme, ''[[The Back Page]]'', formerly hosted by rugby league journalist [[Mike Gibson (sports journalist)|Mike Gibson]] and now [[Tony Squires]]. For the Saturday edition of ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', FitzSimons writes a column titled \"The Fitz Files\" which looks at all the happenings over the past seven days in sport. He writes a more general version of \"The Fitz Files\" in ''[[The Sun-Herald]]'' on Sundays, focusing on community activities and events in Sydney. [[Andrew Denton]] has called him \"Australia's finest sports journalist\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/qanda/txt/s2876991.htm|title=Panelist: Peter FitzSimons|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|work=Q&A|accessdate=26 February 2012}}</ref> On the 25 September 2001 he wrote a thought provoking opinion editorial piece titled Memo world: try saying sorry to avoid a sorry end.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peter FitzSimons |title=Memo world: try saying sorry to avoid a sorry end |url=http://old.smh.com.au/news/0109/25/opinion/opinion3.html |accessdate=20 May 2019 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=25 September 2001 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030205060337/http://old.smh.com.au/news/0109/25/opinion/opinion3.html |archivedate=5 February 2003 |language=en |quote=We accept that such hate as drove the planes into the World Trade Centre towers can only have come from incredible suffering, and we are desperately sorry for that suffering}}</ref>\n\n===Radio===\nIn January 2006 FitzSimons began co-hosting a breakfast radio program with [[Mike Carlton]] on Sydney radio station [[2UE]]. He was brought onto the 2UE breakfast show in an attempt to boost the program's dwindling ratings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/tv--radio/the-odd-couple/2006/01/21/1137734186701.html|title=The odd couple|first=Sue|last=Javes|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=23 January 2006}}</ref> However, the ''Mike and Fitz Breakfast Show'' still trailed a long way behind the number one program on [[2GB]], hosted by FitzSimons' former coach Alan Jones.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/mike-carlton-quits-radio-returns-to-smh/news-story/ec26b075894a690dcbf9d2828de42197|title=Mike Carlton quits 2UE radio breakfast slot|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=7 September 2009}}</ref> After two years, FitzSimons quit to become a [[stay-at-home dad]] and focus on his writing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/radio-battle-for-fitz-vacancy/news-story/3adcb06b27ac54f3ed693620b338cf8f|title=Radio battle for Fitz vacancy|first=Fiona|last=Connolly|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=7 November 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n[[File:Peter FitzSimons (8446505665).jpg|thumb|FitzSimons with his trademark red [[bandana]]<ref>[https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/republic-no-sure-thing-says-peter-fitzsimons/news-story/c28fc89fb3e0ade25fa344b9f75bf3e3 \"Republic no sure thing, says Peter FitzSimons\"] by Ben Packham, ''[[The Australian]]'', 12 November 2018 {{subscription}}</ref>]]\nFitzSimons' published works include:\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Basking in Beirut and other adventures with Peter FitzSimons|publication-date=1991|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-86373-052-5 }}\n* with{{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|author2=Kogler, Brian|title=Little theories of life|publication-date=1991|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-86373-109-6 }}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Rugby stories: some rucking good yarns|publication-date=1993|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-86373-440-0}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Nick Farr-Jones: the authorised biography|publication-date=1993|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=978-0-09-182758-8}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Hitchhiking for ugly people: and other life experiences|publication-date=1994|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=978-0-09-182967-4}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=The rugby war|publication-date=1996|publisher=HarperSports|isbn=978-0-7322-5687-6}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Everyone but Phar Lap: face to face with the best of Australian sport|publication-date=1997|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-7322-6409-3}}\n* with{{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|author2=Blair, Tony|title=Beazley: a biography|publication-date=1998|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-7322-6521-2}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=FitzSimons on rugby: loose in the tight five|publication-date=1999|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-86508-132-8}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Nancy Wake: a biography of our greatest war heroine|publication-date=2001|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-7322-6919-7}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=John Eales: the biography|publication-date=2001|publisher=ABC Books for the Australian Broadcasting Corporation|isbn=978-1-85291-644-2}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Nene|publication-date=2002|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-7322-7565-5}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Steve Waugh|publication-date=2004|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-7322-7647-8}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Tobruk|date=2006|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|location=Pymble|isbn=9780732291563}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|author1=FitzSimons, Peter|author-mask=0|title=Great Australian sports champions|publication-date=2006|publisher=HarperSports|isbn=978-0-7322-8517-3}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=The ballad of Les Darcy|publication-date=2007|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|isbn=978-0-7322-8636-1}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=And now for some light relief: the genuinely funny joke book|publication-date=2009|publisher=Ebury |isbn=978-1-74166-901-5}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Kokoda|date=2010|publisher=Hachette UK|isbn=9780733626067}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Charles Kingsford Smith and those magnificent men|date=2010|publisher=HarperCollins|location=Pymble|isbn=9780732288198}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=A Simpler Time|date=2010|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|location=Pymble|isbn=9780730492511}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Mawson|date=2011|publisher=William Heinemann|location=North Sydney|isbn=9781742754581}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Batavia|date=2012|publisher=Random House Australia|location=North Sydney|isbn=9781864711349}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Eureka: the unfinished revolution|date=2013|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=9780857981271}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|editor1=Growden, Greg|editor2=FitzSimons, Peter|title=More important than life or death: inside the best of Australian sport|publication-date=2013|location=Crows Nest|publisher=Fairfax Books|isbn=978-1-74331-319-0}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Ned Kelly|date=2013|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=9781742758916}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Gallipoli|date=2014|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=9780857984562}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Fromelles and Pozi\u00e8res: In the trenches of Hell|date=2015|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=9781742759517}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Gotta love this country!|publication-date=2015|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-76029-048-1}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=The Great Aussie Bloke Slim-Down: How an Over-50 Former Footballer Went From Fat to Fit... and Lost 45 Kilos|publisher=Penguin Books Australia|publication-date=2016|isbn=9780143781868}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Victory at Villers-Bretonneux: Why a French town will never forget the Anzacs|date=2016|publisher=Random House Australia|isbn=9781742759531}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|others=illustrated by Reg Lynch|title=Seriously ... you have to laugh: great yarns and tall tales from the sporting fields, dressing rooms and commentary boxes of Australia|publication-date=2016|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=978-1-76029-399-4}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Burke and Wills: The Triumph and Tragedy of Australia's Most Famous Explorers|date=2017|publisher=Hachette Australia|isbn=9780733634109}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Monash's masterpiece: the battle of Le Hamel and the 93 minutes that changed the world|publication-date=2018|publisher=Hachette Australia|isbn=978-0-7336-4008-7}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=Mutiny on the Bounty: A saga of sex, sedition, mayhem and mutiny|publication-date=2018|publisher=Hachette Australia|isbn=978-0-7336-3411-6}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=The Catalpa Rescue: The gripping story of the most dramatic and successful prison break in Australian history|publication-date=2019|publisher=Hachette Australia|isbn=978-0-7336-4124-4}}\n* {{cite book|ref=none|last1=FitzSimons|first1=Peter|author-mask=0|title=James Cook: The Story Behind the Man who Mapped the World|publication-date=2019|publisher=Hachette Australia|isbn=978-0-7336-4127-5}}\n\n===Community activity===\nFitzSimons is or was involved with a range of community organisations. He was a fellow of the Senate of [[University of Sydney]] from 2009 to 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sydney.edu.au/senate/FitzSimons.shtml|title=Fellows of the Senate: Peter John FitzSimons|date=|access-date=|publisher=[[University of Sydney]]}}</ref> a [[patronage|patron]] of The [[Russell Prize]] for Humour Writing, [[State Library of New South Wales]], since 2015<ref>[https://www.booksandpublishing.com.au/articles/2014/12/17/32004/nsw-state-library-launches-humour-writing-prize/ \"NSW State Library launches humour-writing prize\"], Books + Publishing, 17 December 2014</ref> and chairman of the [[Australian Republic Movement]] since 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/jul/20/peter-fitzsimons-appointed-head-of-australian-republican-movement|title=Peter FitzSimons appointed head of Australian Republican Movement|date=20 July 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the lead up to [[2019 New South Wales state election]], FitzSimons began a campaign to prevent the demolition of the [[Sydney Football Stadium]] and [[Stadium Australia]]. He began by launching a petition in late 2017 on [[Change.org]] that reached approximately 220,000 signatures prior to the election as well as numerous editorial articles decrying the demolitions. The stadium issue became a major element of the campaign with Labor leader [[Michael Daley]] calling the election a \"referendum on stadiums\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/nsw/i-will-not-be-bullied-daley-holds-firm-on-stadiums-policy-20181202-p50jpa.html |title='I will not be bullied': Daley holds firm on stadiums policy |last=Smith |first=Alexandra |date=3 December 2018|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=4 April 2019 |quote=The new Labor leader says the state election would be a referendum on stadiums}}</ref> On 5 December 2017, FitzSimons remarked on [[Twitter]] that the incumbent [[Gladys Berejiklian]] government could \"bulldoze and rebuild three new stadiums, including Parra, for $3Billion \u2013 on no demand \u2013 or they can win the next election, but they can't do both.\"<ref>{{Cite tweet|author=Peter FitzSimons|user=Peter_Fitz|title=(untitled)|date=5 December 2017|number=937843739736674304}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Berejiklian and her coalition were easily returned to government, with political commentators suggesting that the issue did not resonate with the wider community of the state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-25/the-sydney-stadium-wars-are-over,-and-the-people-have-spoken/10934488 |title=Sydney stadium wars ended by Coalition's NSW election victory as people vote for an upgrade |last=Hinds |first=Richards |date=25 March 2019 |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|access-date=4 April 2019 |quote=it is possible to say with confidence there was one thing Sydneysiders did not vote against \u2014 new or refurbished stadiums.}}</ref> The campaign had a minor success however, as the Government changed the original plan for a complete knock down rebuild of Stadium Australia, and instead would go ahead with a billion dollar refurbishment.\n\n==Personal life==\nFitzSimons is married to Australian journalist and TV presenter [[Lisa Wilkinson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/entertainment/photos-e6frg30l-1226487265216?page=4|title=Galleries: 1992 Weddings|work=[[Perth Now]]|page=4|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> They have three children and live in Sydney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/lifestyle/today-show-hosts-a-perfect-match/story-e6frf039-1225896224840|title=Today show hosts a perfect match|first=Richard|last=Clune|work=[[The Sunday Telegraph (Sydney)|The Sunday Telegraph]]|location=Sydney|date=25 July 2010|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nFitzSimons has identified himself as an [[atheist]] and a [[Australian Republic Movement|republican]].<ref>[http://www.meetup.com/sydneyatheists/events/68134322/ \"Is Religion a Con? A special evening with Peter FitzSimons\"], 12 June 2012, The Independent Theatre</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nOn 13 June 2011 FitzSimons was named a [[Order of Australia|Member of the Order of Australia]] for service to literature as a biographer, sports journalist and commentator, and to the community through contributions to conservation, disability care, social welfare and sporting organisations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peter FitzSimons AM|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1144271&search_type=quick&showInd=true|publisher=Australian Honours Database|accessdate=13 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=[[Australian Associated Press]]|title=Former Wallaby FitzSimons honoured|url=http://my.rugby.com.au/news/aap/s-786352_former_wallaby_fitzsimons_honoured,147625.html/news/archive/section/21893|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120719040442/http://my.rugby.com.au/news/aap/s-786352_former_wallaby_fitzsimons_honoured,147625.html/news/archive/section/21893|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 July 2012|publisher=[[Australian Rugby Union]]|date=13 June 2011|accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{Commons category|Peter FitzSimons}}\n* [http://www.smh.com.au/sport/by/Peter-FitzSimons-hvemu Homepage for FitzSimons' columns] in ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''\n* {{official|http://peterfitzsimons.com.au/}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:FitzSimons, Peter}}\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian biographers]]\n[[Category:Male biographers]]\n[[Category:Australian columnists]]\n[[Category:Australian radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Australian sportswriters]]\n[[Category:Australian television personalities]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian republicans]]\n[[Category:People educated at Knox Grammar School]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Sydney]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Expatriate rugby union players in France]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Australia international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Australian atheists]]\n[[Category:Australian conservationists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Australian memoirists]]\n[[Category:Australian non-fiction crime writers]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8003:cdf8:fe00:91a9:5a7d:1866:23b2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_FitzSimons"}
{"title_page": "ALS Awareness Month", "text_new": "{{Infobox recurring event\n| name = ALS Awareness Month\n| logo =\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| date = {{plainlist|\n* [[Canada]]: June (annually)<ref name=\"Health Canada\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/minist/messages/_2010/2010_06_01-eng.php |title=ALS Awareness Month (Lou Gehrig's Disease) |publisher=[Health Canada] |date=June 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |author=Aglukkaq, Leona |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111063354/http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/minist/messages/_2010/2010_06_01-eng.php |archivedate=January 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n* [[United States]]: May (annually)<ref name=\"MDA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mda.org/news/110502als-awareness.html |title=20th Anniversary of ALS Awareness Month: MDA to Honor 31 Americans |publisher=[Muscular Dystrophy Association] |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718033735/http://www.mda.org/news/110502als-awareness.html |archivedate=July 18, 2011 }}</ref>\n}}\n| begins =\n| ends =\n| frequency =\n| location =\n| years_active = {{plainlist|\n* Canada: {{age|1990|06|01}}\n* United States: {{age|1992|05|01}} <!--Date of the first occurrence-->\n}}\n| first = {{plainlist|\n* Canada: 1990<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.als.ca/en/news/press-releases/june-brings-about-another-als-awareness-month | title=June brings about another ALS awareness month | publisher=[ALS Society of Canada] | date=June 6, 2011 | accessdate=March 30, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504123027/http://www.als.ca/en/news/press-releases/june-brings-about-another-als-awareness-month | archive-date=May 4, 2012 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* United States: 1992<ref name=\"MDA\"/>\n}}\n| last =\n| participants =\n| attendance =\n| organised =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''ALS Awareness Month''' is a campaign to spread awareness of and raise funds for research for a cure for ALS ([[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]], also known as [[Lou Gehrig]]\u2019s Disease).\n\n==Canada==\nIn Canada, June has been declared as ALS Awareness Month by the Canadian Minister of Health.<ref name=\"Health Canada\"/> In 2015, it was recognized by the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.als.ca/en/get-involved/als-awareness|title=ALS Awareness {{!}} ALS Canada|website=als.ca|access-date=2016-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915011941/http://www.als.ca/en/get-involved/als-awareness|archive-date=2016-09-15|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==United States==\nIn the United States, the campaign is observed every year in the month of May.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6017a9.htm | title=Announcements: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS) Awareness Month \u2013 May 2011 | publisher=[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention] | date=May 6, 2011 | accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref> It is recognized by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.cdc.gov/yourhealthyourenvironment/2016/05/02/als-awareness-month-2016/|title=ALS Awareness Month 2016|website=CDC Blogs|publisher=[[Center for Disease Control and Prevention]]|access-date=2016-07-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocacy ===\nDuring this month, the [[ALS Association]] sponsors the National ALS Advocacy Day and Public Policy Conference and leads a delegation of people with ALS, their caregivers and other advocates to [[Capitol Hill]] to urge legislators to support measures to help find treatments and a cure.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}} Other organizations, including the [[ALS Therapy Development Institute]] and the [[Les Turner ALS Foundation]] have their own initiatives.\n\n===Postage stamp===\nIn 2008, the [[ALS Association]] created a commemorative [[Postage stamps and postal history of the United States|U.S. postage stamp]] to promote ALS Awareness Month through [[Zazzle]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://web.alsa.org/site/PageServer?pagename=AAA_Postage_Stamp | title=New ALS Awareness Month Postage Stamp Now On Sale | publisher=[The ALS Association] | date=May 1, 2008 | accessdate=March 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Individual states===\n\n====Georgia====\nIn 2003, [[Georgia Governor]] [[Sonny Perdue]] declared May to be ALS Awareness Month in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sonnyperdue.georgia.gov/gov/proclamations/archive/ALS_AWARENESS_MONTH_Proclamation_2003.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month Proclamation 2003|last=|first=|date=|website=Georgia.gov|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> He repeated this action in 2011. In addition, Governor [[Nathan Deal]] in 2012, 2013,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/site_page/ALS%20Awareness%20Month%202013.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month 2013|last=|first=|date=|website=Georgia.gov|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010184550/https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/site_page/ALS%20Awareness%20Month%202013.pdf|archive-date=2016-10-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> and 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/document/ALS%20Awareness%20Month%202014.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=Georgia.gov|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010184453/https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/document/ALS%20Awareness%20Month%202014.pdf|archive-date=2016-10-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2016, Governor Deal declared January 26 to be ALS Awareness Day in Georgia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/site_page/ALS%20Awareness%20Day%202016.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Day 2016|last=|first=|date=|website=Georgia.gov|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409142448/https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/site_page/ALS%20Awareness%20Day%202016.pdf|archive-date=2016-04-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==== Massachusetts ====\nIn 2016, [[Massachusetts Governor]] [[Charlie Baker]] declared May to be ALS Awareness Month in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mass.gov/governor/constituent-services/recognition/issued-proclamations/2016/als-awareness-month.html|title=ALS Awareness Month 2016|last=|first=|date=|website=mass.gov|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Minnesota ====\nIn 2012, 2013, and 2014, [[Minnesota]] Governor [[Mark Dayton]] declared May to ALS Awareness Month in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mn.gov/governor/assets/ALS_Awareness_Month_tcm1055-92493.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month 2012|last=|first=|date=|website=mn.gov|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818162741/https://mn.gov/governor/assets/ALS_Awareness_Month_tcm1055-92493.pdf|archive-date=2016-08-18|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mn.gov/gov-stat/images/ALS_Awareness_Month-13.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month 2013|last=|first=|date=|website=mn.gov|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mn.gov/governor/assets/ALS_awareness_month_2014.pdf_tcm1055-93323.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=mn.gov|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818191823/https://mn.gov/governor/assets/ALS_awareness_month_2014.pdf_tcm1055-93323.pdf|archive-date=2016-08-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==== North Dakota ====\nIn both May 2014 and May 2016, the Governor of [[North Dakota]] issued proclamations declaring May to be ALS Awareness Month in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://governor.nd.gov/media-center/proclamation/amyotrophic-lateral-sclerosis-als-awareness-month|title=Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS) Awareness Month {{!}} North Dakota Office of the Governor|website=governor.nd.gov|access-date=2016-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://governor.nd.gov/media-center/proclamation/als-awareness-month|title=ALS Awareness Month {{!}} North Dakota Office of the Governor|website=governor.nd.gov|access-date=2016-07-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Ohio ====\nOn January 13, 2012, the 129th [[Ohio General Assembly|General Assembly]] of [[Ohio]] designated the month of May as ALS Awareness Month for the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://codes.ohio.gov/orc/gp5.2267|title=5.2267 ALS Awareness Month|publisher=[Codes.ohio.gov]|accessdate=March 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.nwobserver.com/articles/2011/05/06/news/doc4dc2d304e6b33961275371.txt |title=May is ALS Awareness Month |publisher=[Northwest Observer] |date=May 6, 2011 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |author=Cosgrove, Alicia }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* {{cite web | url=http://abclocal.go.com/kfsn/story?section=news/local&id=8145615 | title=Fresno man showcased during ALS Awareness Month | publisher=[KFSN-TV] | date=May 22, 2011 | accessdate=March 30, 2012 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20130124232125/http://abclocal.go.com/kfsn/story?section=news/local&id=8145615 | archive-date=January 24, 2013 | url-status=dead }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.alsa.org/news/public-awareness/als-awareness-month/2016/landing.html ALS Association]\n* [http://www.als.net/alsmonth/ ALS Therapy Development Institute]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160915011941/http://www.als.ca/en/get-involved/als-awareness ALS Society of Canada]\n* [http://lesturnerals.org/get-involved/awareness-month/ Les Turner ALS Foundation]\n* [http://www.alsbiketrekmn.com ALS Bike Trek MN]\n* [http://www.hopelovescompany.org  Hope Loves Company]\n{{Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis}}\n\n[[Category:May observances]]\n[[Category:June observances|*]]\n[[Category:Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]]\n[[Category:Health observances]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox recurring event\n| name = ALS Awareness Month\n| logo =\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| date = {{plainlist|\n* [[Canada]]: June (annually)<ref name=\"Health Canada\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/minist/messages/_2010/2010_06_01-eng.php |title=ALS Awareness Month (Lou Gehrig's Disease) |publisher=[Health Canada] |date=June 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |author=Aglukkaq, Leona |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111063354/http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ahc-asc/minist/messages/_2010/2010_06_01-eng.php |archivedate=January 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n* [[United States]]: May (annually)<ref name=\"MDA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mda.org/news/110502als-awareness.html |title=20th Anniversary of ALS Awareness Month: MDA to Honor 31 Americans |publisher=[Muscular Dystrophy Association] |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718033735/http://www.mda.org/news/110502als-awareness.html |archivedate=July 18, 2011 }}</ref>\n}}\n| begins =\n| ends =\n| frequency =\n| location =\n| years_active = {{plainlist|\n* Canada: {{age|1990|06|01}}\n* United States: {{age|1992|05|01}} <!--Date of the first occurrence-->\n}}\n| first = {{plainlist|\n* Canada: 1990<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.als.ca/en/news/press-releases/june-brings-about-another-als-awareness-month | title=June brings about another ALS awareness month | publisher=[ALS Society of Canada] | date=June 6, 2011 | accessdate=March 30, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504123027/http://www.als.ca/en/news/press-releases/june-brings-about-another-als-awareness-month | archive-date=May 4, 2012 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* United States: 1992<ref name=\"MDA\"/>\n}}\n| last =\n| participants =\n| attendance =\n| organised =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''ALS Awareness Month''' is a campaign to spread awareness of and raise funds for research for a cure for ALS ([[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]], also known as [[Lou Gehrig]]\u2019s Disease).\n\n==Canada==\nIn Canada, June has been declared as ALS Awareness Month by the Canadian Minister of Health.<ref name=\"Health Canada\"/> In 2015, it was recognized by the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.als.ca/en/get-involved/als-awareness|title=ALS Awareness {{!}} ALS Canada|website=als.ca|access-date=2016-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915011941/http://www.als.ca/en/get-involved/als-awareness|archive-date=2016-09-15|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==United States==\nIn the United States, the campaign is observed every year in the month of May.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6017a9.htm | title=Announcements: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS) Awareness Month \u2013 May 2011 | publisher=[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention] | date=May 6, 2011 | accessdate=March 29, 2012}}</ref> It is recognized by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.cdc.gov/yourhealthyourenvironment/2016/05/02/als-awareness-month-2016/|title=ALS Awareness Month 2016|website=CDC Blogs|publisher=[[Center for Disease Control and Prevention]]|access-date=2016-07-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocacy ===\nDuring this month, the [[ALS Association]] sponsors the National ALS Advocacy Day and Public Policy Conference and leads a delegation of people with ALS, their caregivers and other advocates to [[Capitol Hill]] to urge legislators to support measures to help find treatments and a cure.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}} Other organizations, including the [[ALS Therapy Development Institute]] and the [[Les Turner ALS Foundation]] have their own initiatives.\n\n===Postage stamp===\nIn 2008, the [[ALS Association]] created a commemorative [[Postage stamps and postal history of the United States|U.S. postage stamp]] to promote ALS Awareness Month through [[Zazzle]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://web.alsa.org/site/PageServer?pagename=AAA_Postage_Stamp | title=New ALS Awareness Month Postage Stamp Now On Sale | publisher=[The ALS Association] | date=May 1, 2008 | accessdate=March 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Individual states===\n\n====Georgia====\nIn 2003, [[Georgia Governor]] [[Sonny Perdue]] declared May to be ALS Awareness Month in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sonnyperdue.georgia.gov/gov/proclamations/archive/ALS_AWARENESS_MONTH_Proclamation_2003.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month Proclamation 2003|last=|first=|date=|website=Georgia.gov|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> He repeated this action in 2011. In addition, Governor [[Nathan Deal]] in 2012, 2013,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/site_page/ALS%20Awareness%20Month%202013.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month 2013|last=|first=|date=|website=Georgia.gov|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010184550/https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/site_page/ALS%20Awareness%20Month%202013.pdf|archive-date=2016-10-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> and 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/document/ALS%20Awareness%20Month%202014.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=Georgia.gov|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010184453/https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/document/ALS%20Awareness%20Month%202014.pdf|archive-date=2016-10-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2016, Governor Deal declared January 26 to be ALS Awareness Day in Georgia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/site_page/ALS%20Awareness%20Day%202016.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Day 2016|last=|first=|date=|website=Georgia.gov|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409142448/https://gov.georgia.gov/sites/gov.georgia.gov/files/related_files/site_page/ALS%20Awareness%20Day%202016.pdf|archive-date=2016-04-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==== Massachusetts ====\nIn 2016, [[Massachusetts Governor]] [[Charlie Baker]] declared May to be ALS Awareness Month in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mass.gov/governor/constituent-services/recognition/issued-proclamations/2016/als-awareness-month.html|title=ALS Awareness Month 2016|last=|first=|date=|website=mass.gov|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Minnesota ====\nIn 2012, 2013, and 2014, [[Minnesota]] Governor [[Mark Dayton]] declared May to ALS Awareness Month in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mn.gov/governor/assets/ALS_Awareness_Month_tcm1055-92493.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month 2012|last=|first=|date=|website=mn.gov|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818162741/https://mn.gov/governor/assets/ALS_Awareness_Month_tcm1055-92493.pdf|archive-date=2016-08-18|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mn.gov/gov-stat/images/ALS_Awareness_Month-13.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month 2013|last=|first=|date=|website=mn.gov|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mn.gov/governor/assets/ALS_awareness_month_2014.pdf_tcm1055-93323.pdf|title=ALS Awareness Month 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=mn.gov|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818191823/https://mn.gov/governor/assets/ALS_awareness_month_2014.pdf_tcm1055-93323.pdf|archive-date=2016-08-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==== North Dakota ====\nIn both May 2014 and May 2016, the Governor of [[North Dakota]] issued proclamations declaring May to be ALS Awareness Month in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://governor.nd.gov/media-center/proclamation/amyotrophic-lateral-sclerosis-als-awareness-month|title=Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS) Awareness Month {{!}} North Dakota Office of the Governor|website=governor.nd.gov|access-date=2016-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://governor.nd.gov/media-center/proclamation/als-awareness-month|title=ALS Awareness Month {{!}} North Dakota Office of the Governor|website=governor.nd.gov|access-date=2016-07-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Ohio ====\nOn January 13, 2012, the 129th [[Ohio General Assembly|General Assembly]] of [[Ohio]] designated the month of May as ALS Awareness Month for the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://codes.ohio.gov/orc/gp5.2267|title=5.2267 ALS Awareness Month|publisher=[Codes.ohio.gov]|accessdate=March 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.nwobserver.com/articles/2011/05/06/news/doc4dc2d304e6b33961275371.txt |title=May is ALS Awareness Month |publisher=[Northwest Observer] |date=May 6, 2011 |accessdate=March 30, 2012 |author=Cosgrove, Alicia }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* {{cite web | url=http://abclocal.go.com/kfsn/story?section=news/local&id=8145615 | title=Fresno man showcased during ALS Awareness Month | publisher=[KFSN-TV] | date=May 22, 2011 | accessdate=March 30, 2012 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20130124232125/http://abclocal.go.com/kfsn/story?section=news/local&id=8145615 | archive-date=January 24, 2013 | url-status=dead }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.alsa.org/news/public-awareness/als-awareness-month/2016/landing.html ALS Association]\n* [http://www.als.net/alsmonth/ ALS Therapy Development Institute]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160915011941/http://www.als.ca/en/get-involved/als-awareness ALS Society of Canada]\n* [http://lesturnerals.org/get-involved/awareness-month/ Les Turner ALS Foundation]\n* [http://www.alsbiketrekmn.com ALS Bike Trek MN]\n* [http://www.hopelovescompany.org]\n{{Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis}}\n\n[[Category:May observances]]\n[[Category:June observances|*]]\n[[Category:Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]]\n[[Category:Health observances]]\n", "name_user": "Warren.ames", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added organization name to link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ALS_Awareness_Month"}
